</md></sn><sn><md>### Past Perfect{.text-center}

&gt; **Structure:** Subject + had + $v_3$ + ext <br>
&gt; **Use:** Action that was `completed before another action` in the past <br>
&gt; **বাংলায় ব্যবহার:** অতীতে কোনো কাজ `অন্য একটি কাজের আগে সম্পন্ন` হয়েছে বোঝাতে ব্যবহৃত হয়।

### Fact
* To use past perfect tense we have to compare to event that occured in the past
* if both event occur in the same time they are in the past simple tense
* but one occur before another then the earlier one will be in past perfect and the next event will be in past indefinite tense
* The **Past Perfect Tense** emphasizes the `completion of an event` before another past event, whereas the **Past Perfect Continuous Tense** emphasizes the `continuity or ongoing progress of an event` before another past event, rather than its completion.
* The same distinction applies to the **Future Perfect** and **Future Perfect Continuous Tenses**.


+++ story
Suppose one of your friends visits your house today, and while remembering an earlier day, you ask him:

#### “Did you drink tea before you came to my house yesterday?”

He replies:

#### **"Yes, I had drunk tea before I came."**

Here’s what it means:

* He **finished drinking tea first**, and **then** he **came to your house** — so one action **happened before another past action**.
* This tense shows the **earlier of two past actions**.
* For an action that was **completed before another action in the past**, we use **Past Perfect Tense**.
* Though in both case they represent an event that occur before another event but it depends on what aspect we are emphasizing; based on that, either the **Perfect** or the **Perfect Continuous** tense will be used.If emphasize is on completion then perfect , and else if it is on continuity of that event then prefect continuous.


&gt; **Note:**
&gt; If he had said **"I drank tea before I came"**, it would still mean the same time order, but **"I had drunk tea"** gives a **clearer sense** that the drinking happened **first** and the visiting happened **after**.
