</md></sn><sn><md>### Past Perfect Continuous{.text-center}

&gt; **Structure:** Subject + had been + $v\text{-}ing$ + ext <br>
&gt; **Use:** Action that `started in the past` and `continued up to another time or event` in the past <br>
&gt; **বাংলায় ব্যবহার:** অতীতে কোনো কাজ `একটি নির্দিষ্ট সময় বা ঘটনার আগে পর্যন্ত চলছিল` বোঝাতে ব্যবহৃত হয়।

### Fact

* The **Past Perfect Continuous Tense** inherits its properties from the **Past Perfect Tense**, so it is used for an action that **occurred before another past event**.
* However, this tense `emphasizes the continuous or ongoing nature` of the action during that earlier time.


+++ story
Suppose one of your friends visits your house today, and while remembering an earlier day, you ask him:

#### “What were you doing before you came to my house yesterday?”

He replies:

#### **"I had been drinking tea before I came."**

Here’s what it means:

* He **started drinking tea earlier** and **continued for some time** before he **came to your house**.
* The action of **drinking tea** was **in progress for a period of time** before another past action (**coming to your house**) took place.
* This tense shows the **duration or continuity** of an action that **was happening up to a certain point in the past**.

&gt; **Note:**
&gt; We use **Past Perfect Continuous Tense** to show that an action **was going on for some time** **before another action in the past**.

**Example Structure:**

&gt; I had been drinking tea before you called me.

It means he was `in the middle of drinking tea` when or just before the **other past event** occurred.
